TASKS

Connectivity between three routers has been established, and IP services must be configured in the order presented to complete the implementation.
Tasks assigned include configuration of NAT, NTP, DHCP, and SSH services.

1. All traffic sent from R3 to the R1 Loopback address must be configured for NAT on R2. All source addresses must be translated from R3 to the IP address of Ethernet0/0 on R2, while using only a standard access list named NAT. To verify, a ping must be successful to the R1 Loopback address sourced from R3. Do not use NVI NAT configuration.

2. Configure R1 as an NTP server and R2 as a client, not as a peer, using the IP address of the R1 Ethernet0/2 interface. Set the clock on the NTP server for midnight on January 1, 2019.

3. Configure R1 as a DHCP server for the network 10.1.3.0/24 in a pool named NETPOOL. Using a single command, exclude addresses 1-10 from the range. Interface Ethernet0/2 on R3 must be issued the IP address of 10.1.3.11 via DHCP.

4. Configure SSH connectivity from R1 to R3, while excluding access via other remote connection protocols. Access for user netadmin and password N3t4ccess must be set on router R3 using RSA and 1024 bits. Verify connectivity using an SSH session from router R1 using a destination address of 10.1.3.11.

Do NOT modify console access or line numbers to accomplish this task.

SOLUTION

1. All traffic sent from R3 to the R1 Loopback address must be configured for NAT on R2.

This means that we need to identify traffic coming from any of R3's interfaces as it passes through R2.
We can achieve this by matching traffic using an ACL.

The ACL will be used to identify if the IP addresses on the packets came from R3's interfaces.

*NOTE: The name of the access list may be different so read the instructions carefully.  

@R2
conf t
 ip access-list standard NAT
  permit 10.2.3.3
  permit 192.168.3.1
  permit 10.1.3.11
  exit
  end
Now that we have a way to identify the traffic, it is instructed that the packets that came from R3 will be configured for NAT on R2, then will be translated based on the IP on R2's e0/0 interface.

In this case, we can consider that the interface on R2 (e0/1) that is connected to R3 will be the INSIDE since the packets will come FROM R3, then OUTSIDE will be R2's e0/0 interface.

@R2
conf t
 int e0/1
  ip nat inside
  exit
 int e0/0
  ip nat outside
  exit
 ip nat inside source list NAT interface e0/0 overload
 end
The NAT command simply states:

Packets that enters the INSIDE interface (e0/1) and is specified by the list, NAT, will be translated to the IP address on the router's (R2) e0/0 interface (10.1.2.2).

Then makes use of not only the ip (10.1.2.2) but also port numbers (Overload) to keep track of translated IP addresses.

VERIFY:

@R3
ping 192.168.1.1



2. Configure R1 as an NTP server and R2 as a client, not as a peer, using the IP address of the R1 Ethernet0/2 interface.

@R1
conf t
 ntp master 1
 ntp source e0/2
 end
The master command will set R1 as an NTP server with a stratum 1.
    Stratum represents distance from a reference clock.
    ex.
        If a clock A is referencing clock B that is also referencing clock C that is referencing an atomic clock (Stratum 0 = The most accurate)
        The stratum value of clock B on clock A's perspective is 2.

        Stratum ranges from 0-15. Anything highing will be unsynchronized. Therefore unreliable.


The ntp source command will simply specify what interface ip address R1 is gonna use when responding to NTP clients. By default it would have referenced the closes interface to the client.

In the case of R2 being the client, the default source interface would have been R1's e0/0 interface.


Set the clock on the NTP server for midnight on January 1, 2019.

@R1
clock set 00:00:00 January 1 2019
@R2
conf t
 ntp server 10.1.3.1
 end
Verify: NTP Takes a while to synchronize.

@R2
show ntp association


3. Configure R1 as a DHCP server for the network 10.1.3.0/24 in a pool named NETPOOL. Using a single command, exclude addresses 1-10 from the range.

Interface Ethernet0/2 on R3 must be issued the IP address of 10.1.3.11 via DHCP.

@R1
conf t
 !- always start with the exclusion just so that a client won't be able to obtain the IP.
 !
 ip dhcp excluded-address 10.1.3.1 10.1.3.10
 !
 ip dhcp pool NETPOOL
  network 10.1.3.0 255.255.255.0
  end
No other DHCP options was specified from the task so we only set the bare minimum configuration for DHCP that is enough for it to function.

Interface Ethernet0/2 on R3 must be issued the IP address of 10.1.3.11 via DHCP.

@R3
conf t
 int e0/2
  no shut
  ip add dhcp
  end
Verify:

Wait for a bit as the DHCP states takes place (Discover, Offer, Request, Acknowledge).
Then,

@R3
show ip interface brief
R3 MUST have the IP 10.1.3.11 on its e0/2 interface.

Also, you can verify from R1 to check if it was really the one that gave the IP to R3.

@R1
show ip dhcp binding


4. Configure SSH connectivity from R1 to R3, while excluding access via other remote connection protocols.

@R3
conf t
 line vty 0 4
  transport input ssh
  login local
  end
*NOTE: Devices in this simulation only have 5 vty lines (0-4)

Older devices only had 5, recent ones more 16+

To check how many vty lines a device has,

@Cisco Device
show run | s line
Access for user netadmin and password N3t4ccess must be set on router R3 using RSA and 1024 bits.

@R3
conf t
 username netadmin password N3t4ccess
 crypto key generate rsa modulus 1024 
 end
*NOTE: The specified username and password might be different so check carefully. Also, whether to use a secret or password command depends on what is being asked.


If they asked that the password is a secret, or the password must be hashed with md5, then use the secret command.

Verify connectivity using an SSH session from router R1 using a destination address of 10.1.3.11.

Do NOT modify console access or line numbers to accomplish this task.

@R1
ssh -l netadmin 10.1.3.11
*Note: -l is L for login


