Services must be configured in the order presented to complete the implementation.

1. Configure dynamic one-to-one address mapping on R2 using a standard list named XLATE, which allows all traffic to translate the source address of R3 to a pool named test_pool using the 10.10.10.0/24 network for traffic sent from R3 to R1.
Avoid using an NVI configuration.

Verify reachability by sending a ping to 192.168.100.1 from R3.
2. Configure R3 to dynamically receive an IP address on Ethernet0/2 from the DHCP server.
3. Configure R1 as an NTP server and R2 as a client, not as a peer,
using the IP address 10.1.2.1.
4. Configure SSH access from R1 to R3, while excluding access via other remote connection protocols using the user root and password s3cret on router R3 using RSA.
Verify connectivity from router R1 to R3 using a destination address assigned to interface E0/2 on R3.

SOLUTION

1. Configure dynamic one-to-one address mapping on R2 using a standard list named XLATE, which allows all traffic to translate the source address of R3 to a pool named test_pool using the 10.10.10.0/24 network for traffic sent from R3 to R1.

Avoid using an NVI configuration.

Let's create the ACL first that will match traffic from coming from any of R3's interfaces.

@R2
conf t
 ip access-list standard XLATE
  permit 10.2.3.3
  permit 192.168.3.1
  permit 10.1.3.11
  end
Then we need a NAT pool for translating addresses. It is specified to use all IPs from the network 10.10.10.0/24

Which means the first valid IP will be 10.10.10.1

And the last valid IP will be 10.10.10.254

@R2
conf t
 ip nat pool test_pool 10.10.10.1 10.10.10.254 netmask 255.255.255.0
 end
Finally, complete the NAT configurations by specifying INSIDE and OUTSIDE interfaces.

Followed with the INSIDE NAT configuration.

@R2
conf t
 int e0/1
  ip nat inside
  exit
 int e0/0
  ip nat outside
  exit
 ip nat inside source list XLATE pool test_pool
 end
This command simply says that:

Packets that enters the INSIDE interface that matches what's specified on the list (XLATE) will be translated from a pool of addresses from the pool test_pool.

We will not use the overload command because it is specified "One-to-One" meaning one IP address to one IP address translation.

Devices MUST not share the same OUTSIDE IP.


VERIFY:

@R3
ping 192.168.100.1
R3 was not configured with any routing, neither is R1 or R2. R3 was able to ping R1's loopback interface because of the NAT configurations.







